# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: battery-management-system
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] The individual cells in a battery pack naturally have somewhat different capacities, and so, over the course of charge and discharge cycles, may be at a different state of charge (SOC).
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Balancing a multi-cell pack helps to maximize capacity and service life of the pack by working to maintain equivalent state-of-charge of every cell, to the degree possible given their different capacities, over the widest possible range.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Balancing is only necessary for packs that contain more than one cell in series.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Parallel cells will naturally balance since they are directly connected to each other, but groups of parallel wired cells, wired in series (parallel-series wiring) must be balanced between cell groups.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] To ensure safe operation and prevent hazardous conditions, the battery management system (BMS) continuously tracks critical parameters like temperature and voltage at the individual cell level, detecting any potential deviations that could lead to failure.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] While current is typically monitored at the pack level to optimize performance, the BMS may include one-shot protection mechanisms at the cell level to rapidly disconnect cells in case of an abnormally high current, such as during a short circuit or other fault conditions.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Under normal operation, discharging must stop when any cell first runs out of charge even though other cells may still hold significant charge.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Likewise, charging must stop when any cell reaches its maximum safe charging voltage.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Failure to do either may cause permanent damage to the cells, or in extreme cases, may drive cells into reverse polarity, cause internal gassing, thermal runaway, or other catastrophic failures.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] If the cells are not balanced, such that the high and low cutoff are at least aligned with the state of the lowest capacity cell, the energy that can be taken from and returned to the battery will be limited.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Because lithium chemistries often permit flexible membrane structures, lithium cells can be deployed in flexible though sealed bags, which permits higher packing densities within a battery pack.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] When a lithium cell is mistreated, some of the breakdown products (usually of electrolyte chemicals or additives) outgas.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Such cells will become 'puffy' and are very much on the way to failure.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] In sealed lithium-ion cylindrical-format batteries, the same outgassing has caused rather large pressures (800+ psi has been reported); such cells can explode if not provided with a pressure relief mechanism.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Compounding the danger is that many lithium cell chemistries include hydrocarbon chemicals (the exact nature of which is typically proprietary), and these are flammable.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Therefore, in addition to the risk of cell mistreatment potentially causing an explosion, a simple non-explosive leak can cause a fire.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Most battery chemistries have less dramatic, and less dangerous, failure modes.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] The chemicals in most batteries are often toxic to some degree, but are rarely explosive or flammable; many are corrosive, which accounts for advice to avoid leaving batteries inside equipment for long periods as the batteries may leak and damage the equipment.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Lead acid batteries are an exception, for charging them generates hydrogen gas, which can explode if exposed to an ignition source (e.g., a lit cigarette ) and such an explosion will spray sulfuric acid in all directions.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Since this is corrosive and potentially blinding, this is a particular danger.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] In active balancing, the balancer circuit enables transfer of charge between different cells of the battery, i.e., transferring energy from cells with a higher charge to cells with a lower charge.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] The term *battery regulator* typically refers only to devices that perform passive balancing.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] A full BMS might include active balancing as well as temperature monitoring, charging, and other features to maximize the life of a battery pack.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Typically, the power handled by each DC-DC converter is a few orders of magnitude lower than the power handled by the battery pack as a whole.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] In passive balancing, energy is drawn from the most charged cell and dissipated as heat, usually through resistors.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Passive balancing equalizes the state of charge at some fixed point—usually either "top balanced", with all cells reaching 100% SOC at the same time; or "bottom balanced", with all cells reaching minimum SOC at the same time.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Passive balancing is inherently wasteful, with some of the pack's energy spent as heat for the sake of equalizing the state of charge between cells.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] The build-up of waste heat may also limit the rate at which balancing can occur.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] In active balancing, energy may be drawn from the most charged cell and transferred to the least charged cells, e.g., through capacitor-based, inductor-based, or DC-DC converters.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Active balancing attempts to redistribute energy from cells at full charge to those with a lower state of charge.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Energy can be bled from a cell at higher SOC by switching a reservoir capacitor in-circuit with the cell, then disconnecting the capacitor and reconnecting it to a cell with lower SOC, or through a DC-to-DC converter connected across the entire pack.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Due to inefficiencies, some energy is still wasted as heat, but not to the same degree.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] Despite the obvious advantages, the additional cost and complexity of an active balancing topology can be substantial, and doesn't always make sense depending on the application.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-balancing] This has the advantage of reducing pack weight slightly and lowering parasitic draw, as well as permitting multi-point balancing.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] A battery pack built together with a BMS with an external communication data bus is a smart battery pack.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] A smart battery pack must be charged by a smart battery charger.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Battery thermal management systems can be either passive or active, and the cooling medium can either be air, liquid, or some form of phase change.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Air cooling is advantageous in its simplicity.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Such systems can be passive, relying only on the convection of the surrounding air, or active, using fans for airflow.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Commercially, the Honda Insight and Toyota Prius both use active air cooling of their battery systems.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The major disadvantage of air cooling is its inefficiency.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Large amounts of power must be used to operate the cooling mechanism, far more than active liquid cooling.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The additional components of the cooling mechanism also add weight to the BMS, reducing the efficiency of batteries used for transportation.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Liquid cooling has a higher natural cooling potential than air cooling as liquid coolants tend to have higher thermal conductivities than air.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The batteries can either be directly submerged in the coolant or the coolant can flow through the BMS without directly contacting the battery.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Indirect cooling has the potential to create large thermal gradients across the BMS due to the increased length of the cooling channels.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] This can be reduced by pumping the coolant faster through the system, creating a tradeoff between pumping speed and thermal consistency.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The central controller of a BMS communicates internally with its hardware operating at a cell level, or externally with high level hardware such as laptops or an HMI.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Low-voltage centralized BMSes mostly do not have any internal communications.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Distributed or modular BMSes must use some low-level internal cell–controller (modular architecture) or controller–controller (distributed architecture) communication.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] These types of communications are difficult, especially for high-voltage systems.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The problem is the voltage shift between cells.The first cell ground signal may be hundreds of volts higher than the other cell ground signal.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Apart from software protocols, there are two known ways of hardware communication for voltage shifting systems, optical-isolator and wireless communication.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Another restriction for internal communications is the maximum number of cells.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] For modular architecture, most hardware is limited to a maximum of 255 nodes.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] For high-voltage systems the seeking time of all cells is another restriction, limiting minimum bus speeds and losing some hardware options.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The cost of modular systems is important, because it may be comparable to the cell price.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] To bypass power limitations of existing USB cables due to heat from electric current, communication protocols implemented in mobile phone chargers for negotiating an elevated voltage have been developed, the most widely used of which are Qualcomm Quick Charge and MediaTek Pump Express.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] More recently, the USB Power Delivery standard aims for a universal negotiation protocol across devices of up to 240 watts.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] A BMS may also feature a precharge system allowing a safe way to connect the battery to different loads and eliminating the excessive inrush currents to load capacitors.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The connection to loads is normally controlled through electromagnetic relays called contactors.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] The precharge circuit can be either power resistors connected in series with the loads until the capacitors are charged.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Alternatively, a switched mode power supply connected in parallel to loads can be used to charge the voltage of the load circuit up to a level close enough to the battery voltage in to allow closing the contactors between the battery and load circuit.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] A BMS may have a circuit that can check whether a relay is already closed before recharging (due to welding for example) to prevent inrush currents from occurring.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] In order to maximize the battery's capacity, and to prevent localized under-charging or over-charging, the BMS may actively ensure that all the cells that compose the battery are kept at the same voltage or State of Charge, through balancing.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Some chargers accomplish the balance by charging each cell independently.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] This is often performed by the BMS and not the charger (which typically provides only the bulk charge current, and does not interact with the pack at the cell-group level), e.g., e-bike and hoverboard chargers.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] In this method, the BMS will request a lower charge current (such as EV batteries), or will shut-off the charging input (typical in portable electronics) through the use of transistor circuitry while balancing is in effect (to prevent over-charging cells).
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Centralized BMSs are the most economical, least expandable, and are plagued by a multitude of wires.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Distributed BMSs are the most expensive, simplest to install, and offer the cleanest assembly.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Modular BMSes offer a compromise of the features and problems of the other two topologies.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] In the case of electric or hybrid vehicles, the BMS is only a subsystem and cannot work as a stand-alone device.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] It must communicate with at least a charger (or charging infrastructure), a load, thermal management and emergency shutdown subsystems.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Therefore, in a good vehicle design the BMS is tightly integrated with those subsystems.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Some small mobile applications (such as medical equipment carts, motorized wheelchairs, scooters, and forklifts) often have external charging hardware, however the on board BMS must still have tight design integration with the external charger.
[src:battery-management-system/battery-management-system] Various battery balancing methods are in use, some of them based on state of charge theory.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] In a battery electric vehicle (BEV), the state of charge indicates the remaining energy in the battery pack.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] The state of charge can help to reduce electrical car owners' anxiety when they are waiting in the line or stay at home since it will reflect the progress of charging and let owners know when it will be ready.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] However on any vehicle dashboard, especially in plug-in hybrid vehicles, the state of charge presented as a gauge or percentage value may not be representative of a real level of charge.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] A noticeable amount of energy may be reserved for hybrid-work operations.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Examples of such cars are Mitsubishi Outlander PHEV (all versions/years of production), where a charge level of zero is indicated to the driver when the real charge level is 20–22%.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Another one is the BMW i3 REX (Range Extender version), where about 6% of SoC is reserved for PHEV-alike operations.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] State of charge is also known to impact battery aging.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] To extend battery lifetime, extremes of state of charge should be avoided and reduced variations windows are also preferable.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Usually, SoC cannot be measured directly but it can be estimated from direct measurement variables in two ways: offline and online.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] In offline techniques, the battery desires to be charged and discharged in constant rate such as Coulomb-counting.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] This method gives precise estimation of battery SoC, but they are protracted, costly, and interrupt main battery performance.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Therefore, researchers are looking for some online techniques.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] This method works only with batteries that offer access to their liquid electrolyte, such as non-sealed lead acid batteries.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] The specific gravity of the electrolyte can be used to indicate the SoC of the battery.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Hydrometers are used to calculate the specific gravity of a battery.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] To find specific gravity, it is necessary to measure out volume of the electrolyte and to weigh it.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Then specific gravity is given by (mass of electrolyte [g]/ volume of electrolyte [ml])/ (Density of Water, i.e.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] To find SoC from specific gravity, a look-up table of SG vs SoC is needed.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Refractometry has been shown to be a viable method for continuous monitoring of the state of charge.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] The refractive index of the battery electrolyte is directly relatable to the specific gravity or density of the electrolyte of the cell.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Notably, analysis of electrolyte does not provide information about the state-of-charge in the case of lithium-ion batteries and other batteries, that do not produce or consume solvent or dissolved species during their operation.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] This method converts a reading of the battery voltage to SoC, using the known discharge curve (voltage vs.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] However, the voltage is more significantly affected by the battery current (due to the battery's electrochemical kinetics) and temperature.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] This method can be made more accurate by compensating the voltage reading by a correction term proportional to the battery current, and by using a look-up table of battery's open circuit voltage vs. temperature.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] In fact, it is a stated goal of battery design to provide a voltage as constant as possible no matter the SoC, which makes this method difficult to apply.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] For batteries, that have voltage independent on their state-of-charge (such as lithium iron phosphate battery), open-circuit voltage measurements cannot provide a reliable estimate of the SoC.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] On the other hand, batteries with a sloping voltage-charge curves (such as nickel-cobalt-manganese battery), are more amenable to SoC estimation from the open-circuit voltage measurements.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] This method, also known as *coulomb counting*, calculates the SoC by measuring the battery current and integrating it in time.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] Maxim Integrated touts a combined voltage and charge approach that is claimed superior to either method alone; it is implemented in their ModelGauge m3 series of chips, such as MAX17050, which is used in the Nexus 6 and Nexus 9 Android devices, for example.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] To overcome the shortcomings of the voltage method and the current integration method, a Kalman filter can be used.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] The battery can be described with an electrical model which the Kalman filter will use to predict the over-voltage given the observed current.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] In combination with coulomb counting, it can make an accurate estimation of the state of charge.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] The strength of this technique is that a Kalman filter adjusts its relative trust of the battery voltage and coulomb counting in real time.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] This method can be used with certain NiMH batteries, whose internal pressure increases rapidly when the battery is charged.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] More commonly, a pressure switch indicates if the battery is fully charged.
[src:battery-management-system/coulomb-counting] This method may be improved by taking into account Peukert's law which is a function of charge/discharge current.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] 2. the fraction of the battery's capacity which is *currently* removed from the battery with regard to its (fully) charged state.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] For fully charged batteries, the depth of discharge is connected to the state of charge by the simple formula $\mathrm {DoD} =1-\mathrm {SoC}$ .
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] The depth of discharge then is the complement of state of charge: as one increases, the other decreases.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] This definition is mostly found in scientific sources.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] The depth of discharge can therefore (1) refer to the size of the range usually used for discharge or (2) the *current* amount of charge or fraction of the capacity removed from the battery.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] To avoid confusion, the exact meaning of DoD should be clear for a given context.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] Also, for both definitions, it remains undefined, whether a charged battery's SoC is 100 % or another value.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] This reference value is needed to fully describe (1) the *upper and lower limit* of absolute SoC used for operation or (2) the *current value* of the absolute SoC.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] During their use, secondary batteries are repeatedly charged and discharged within a certain range of state of charge.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] For many battery types, it is beneficial or even mandatory for safety reasons, to not encounter overcharging and/or deep discharge.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] To prevent adverse effects, a battery management system or battery charger may keep the battery from extreme levels regarding SoC, thereby limiting the SoC to a reduced range between 0 % and 100 % and decreasing *depth of discharge* below 100 % (see example below).
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] This corresponds to the DoD in the sense of definition (1).
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] For almost all known rechargeable battery technologies, such as lead-acid batteries of all kinds like AGM, there is a correlation between the depth of discharge and the cycle life of the battery.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] For LiFePO 4 batteries, for example, the state of charge is often limited to the range between 15 % and 85 % to greatly increase their cycle life, resulting in a DoD of 70 %.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] While the state of charge is usually expressed using percentage points (0 % = empty; 100 % = full), depth of discharge is either expressed using units of Ah (e.g. for a 50 Ah battery, 0 Ah is full and 50 Ah is empty) or percentage points (100 % is empty and 0 % is full).
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] The capacity of a battery may also be higher than its nominal rating.
[src:battery-management-system/depth-of-discharge] Thus it is possible for the depth of discharge value to exceed the nominal value (e.g., 55 Ah for a 50 Ah battery, or 110 %).
